[The report states that investigational therapeutics are now in-country and all protocols have been approved by the Ethics Review Board (ERB). While they were not able to be tested in this outbreak, when the next outbreak occurs, these antivirals will be in place to be implemented immediately. Other aspects of preparedness including training of personnel, raising of awareness of virus transmission, stocking of supplies, and more also seem to be in place, potentially facilitating rapid response to future outbreaks. It is important that the basic health infrastructure that has been established be maintained and not allowed to lapse into dysfunction once the outbreak is truly over. - Mod.LK]

- 21 Jun 2018. Influx of suspected, ruled-out cases continues in DRC Ebola outbreak
[Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy (CIDRAP), edited]
http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2018/06/news-scan-jun-21-2018

In the latest development in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) Ebola outbreak, the country's health ministry yesterday [20 Jun 2018] reported 3 new suspected cases in Bikoro, 1 of the 2 remote hotspots, according to a daily update.

Tests on earlier suspected cases ruled out 2 infections, which puts the overall total at 61 cases, including 38 confirmed, 14 probable, and 9 suspected illnesses. The fatality count held steady at 28.

A vaccination campaign in the affected area continues with the experimental VSV-EBOV vaccine, and so far 3139 people have been immunized, the vast majority of them in Iboko and Bikoro, the 2 locations in the forested region where most of the illnesses have occurred.

The last confirmed case-patient became ill on 2 Jun 2018. Though the number of lab-confirmed cases has tapered off, the World Health Organization (WHO) said yesterday [20 Jun 2018] in an outbreak update that the trend is promising, "However, in spite of progress, there should be no room for laxity and complacency until the outbreak is controlled. The focus of operations remains on intensive surveillance and active case finding."

