[It would be great to see a presentation of studies similar to this for the experimental treatment, antibody 114, described in the next report. - Mod.LK]

- 21 Jun 2018. Experimental treatment
[Radio Okapi, in French, machine trans., edited]
https://www.radiookapi.net/2018/06/21/actualite/sante/rdc-100-de-singes-gueris-apres-le-traitement-experimental-anti-ebola

100 percent of monkeys infected with the Ebola virus were cured after treatment with antibody 114, an experimental treatment developed by the National Institute of Biomedical Research (INRB). The Director General of this Institute, Dr Muyembe said [Wed 20 Jun 2018], at the opening of the IX International Congress on Infectious and Parasitic Pathologies, held in Lubumbashi [DRC] with the theme: "Infectious Diseases, Comorbidities, Global Health and environment."

"We know better and better the pathogen and we have developed a treatment. So far, it's still [in the experimental phase]. It is called the 114 antibody, when we inject it into monkeys that are infected and that make the disease Ebola, 100 percent cure ", said Dr Muyembe, who said the research is promising.

The director general added that the next step in this research is the injection of antibody 114 into humans to track their response to infected people.

"Now it's the passage to take this antibody and use it in humans. If it works in the man at the moment we will say that we have total control of this epidemic, " he said.

The Rector of UNILU [University of Lubumbashi] acknowledged that the congress on infectious diseases is an asset to bring remedies and solutions to the Ebola crisis, which is still a plural and multifaceted crisis. Beyond Ebola, delegates will also reflect on other infectious diseases including malaria, HIV AIDS, and the strain of sleeping sickness.

The conference, which opened [Wed 20 Jun 2018], ends [Fri 22 Jun 2018]. It is organized by the INRB, in collaboration with the University of Lubumbashi. Researchers from the United States, Europe, Asia, Africa, and some cities in the DRC are taking part.

--
